## The Pillow Premium

The Pillow Premium at 3ct follows the same pattern as at 2ct — cushion cuts cost more than princess cuts of equivalent quality, not less — but the absolute premium in dollars is larger. At 3ct GIA G-VVS2, the cushion is $32,692. A princess cut at 3ct GIA G-VVS2 quality typically runs $26,000–$28,000. The cushion premium at 3ct is $4,000–$6,000 — real money at this price level.

[![Cushion cut diamond engagement ring yellow gold solitaire on white background](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/BrioSuperImposeBox/Rings/505021/505021_M1_CSH_DIM_wht_0100CT_W_Box3_004_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?ShapeID=Cushion&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

The demand dynamic at 3ct is more pronounced than at 2ct: there are fewer natural 3ct cushion rough crystals that yield the right dimensions for a square cushion shape, and fewer buyers who reach this budget (which reduces but does not eliminate competition). The result is a thin, premium-priced natural 3ct cushion market where entry-level stones ($32,692) sit far above what a comparable princess cut costs.

**In the lab market at 3ct, The Pillow Premium largely disappears.** Lab production of 3ct cushion modified brilliants is abundant, and the GIA 3ct D-VVS1 at $5,962 and a comparable lab 3ct princess are within a similar price range. For buyers choosing between lab cushion and lab princess at 3ct, aesthetics should drive the decision — not price expectations.

For a full analysis of The Pillow Premium across carat weights, see the [2 carat cushion cut diamond ring guide](/2-carat-cushion-cut-diamond-ring) where this concept is explored in detail at the point where it first becomes significant.

