**The Certification Gap anomaly at 3ct D-VVS1:** GIA D-VVS1 ($5,962) is priced lower than IGI D-VVS1 ($6,215) — the usual GIA premium is reversed at this quality tier due to supply dynamics. The [GIA D-VVS1 at $5,962](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/26315453?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the single best value recommendation in this post: prestige certification, top colour, clean clarity, and the lowest price in the lab table. For complete coverage of this phenomenon, see the [lab grown cushion cut diamond guide](/lab-grown-cushion-cut-diamond).

**The D-IF tier at 3ct:** IGI D-IF at $9,327 versus GIA D-IF at $14,267 — a $4,940 difference for the same stated quality. At 3ct, IF clarity in a modified brilliant is not visible as a quality improvement over VVS1 to any eye. The premium is purely certificatory. The $3,365 savings of D-VVS1 over D-IF (at GIA pricing) buys an exceptional setting with change remaining.

> "The clarity question at 3ct cushion gets answered wrong more often than at any other size because the internet advice — 'crushed ice hides inclusions, buy SI1' — is not false but is incomplete. It is true that the modified brilliant pattern makes SI1 inclusions less visible than in a round or emerald cut of the same clarity. It is also true that at 9mm face-up, a poorly positioned SI1 inclusion in a 3ct cushion is visible. These facts are not contradictory — they are both true simultaneously, and the resolution is the HD video, not the clarity grade alone.
>
> In the lab market at 3ct, where D-VVS1 starts at $5,962, the clarity debate is moot. There is no financial reason to compromise on clarity in the lab 3ct tier. VVS1 is the entry grade, not a premium." — Farzana Hasan, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**

